DAKAR â€“ Democratic Republic of Congo's mining sector paid $1.57-billion in revenues to the government last year, up 91% on 2017, finance ministry data showed on Wednesday. Public revenues from the oil and gas sector fell by 19% in 2018 to $165.6-million, according to the data. Mining production in Congo, Africa's top copper producer and the world's leading miner of cobalt, a key component in electric car batteries, rose sharply last year.